The problem is that the index in the array `rows` starts at zero, not one. 
So when we use `rows[2]`, it refers to the third element in the list, which
which is not what we intended - we want the record with label "target". 

To fix this, you can change the code to find the selected row by iterating 
over all rows and looking for a match on the 'label' field. Here is how you
you could do it:

```tundra
val rows = [
  { label: "low", value: 10 },
  { label: "target", value: 20 },
  { label: "high", value: 30 }
];

var selected = null;
for (var i = 0; i < rows.length; i++) {
  if (rows[i].label == "target") {
    selected = rows[i];
    break;
  }
}
print(selected.value);
```

This program uses a for loop to iterate over all the records in `rows` and 
checks each one's 'label'. When it finds a record with label "target", it a
assigns that record to `selected` and exits the loop. Finally, it prints ou
out the value of the selected record. It should now correctly output 20.
